goals.question: What is the distribution of population across different zip codes?
goals.rationale: This visualization will help us understand the spread of population across different zip codes and identify any outliers or patterns.

goals.question: What is the average income of households in different zip codes?
goals.visualization: Bar chart of income field grouped by zip code
goals.rationale: This visualization will help us identify the zip codes with higher average income and compare it with other zip codes.

goals.question: What is the distribution of age across different zip codes?
goals.visualization: Box plot of age field grouped by zip code
goals.rationale: This visualization will help us identify the zip codes with higher median age and compare it with other zip codes.

goals.question: What is the relationship between population and number of businesses in a zip code?
goals.visualization: Scatter plot of population vs number of businesses
goals.rationale: This visualization will help us identify any correlation between population and number of businesses in a zip code.

goals.question: What is the distribution of housing units across different zip codes?
goals.rationale: This visualization will help us understand the spread of housing units across different zip codes and identify any outliers or patterns.

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd
def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data['population'].plot(kind='hist', bins=50, color='blue', edgecolor='black', alpha=0.7)
    plt.axvline(data['population'].mean(), color='red', linestyle='dashed', linewidth=1, label=f"Mean: {data['population'].mean():0.2f}")
    plt.axvline(data['population'].median(), color='green', linestyle='dashed', linewidth=1, label=f"Median: {data['population'].median():0.2f}")
    plt.legend()
    plt.title('What is the distribution of population across different zip codes?', wrap=True)
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd
def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data['income'] = data['income'].astype(float)
    income_by_zip = data.groupby('zip_code')['income'].mean().reset_index()
    plt.bar(income_by_zip['zip_code'], income_by_zip['income'])
    plt.title('What is the average income of households in different zip codes?', wrap=True)
    plt.xlabel('Zip Code')
    plt.ylabel('Average Income')
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd
def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data['age'] = pd.to_numeric(data['age'], errors='coerce')
    data = data.dropna(subset=['age'])
    data = data.groupby('zip_code')['age'].apply(list).reset_index(name='age')
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10, 6))
    ax.boxplot(data['age'])
    ax.set_xticklabels(data['zip_code'])
    plt.title('What is the distribution of age across different zip codes?', wrap=True)
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd
def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    plt.scatter(data['population'], data['number_of_businesses'])
    plt.title('What is the relationship between population and number of businesses in a zip code?', wrap=True)
    plt.xlabel('Population')
    plt.ylabel('Number of Businesses')
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd
def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data['housing_units'] = pd.to_numeric(data['housing_units'], errors='coerce')
    data = data.dropna(subset=['housing_units'])
    plt.hist(data['housing_units'], bins=50, color='blue', alpha=0.5)
    plt.axvline(data['housing_units'].median(), color='red', linestyle='dashed', linewidth=1, label='Median: {:.2f}'.format(data['housing_units'].median()))
    plt.xlabel('Housing Units')
    plt.ylabel('Frequency')
    plt.legend(loc='upper right')
    plt.title('What is the distribution of housing units across different zip codes?', wrap=True)
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)
